ncertainty as to how the selected parameters will affect the final objective. Through a sequential and easy-to-understand discussion, Hespanha examines how to make sure that the selection leads to acceptable performance, even in the presence of uncertainty-the unforgiving variable that can wreck engineering designs. Hespanha looks at such standard topics as zero-sum, non-zero-sum, and dynamics games and includes a MATLAB guide to coding.Noncooperative Game Theory offers students a fresh way of approaching engineering and computer science applications.An introduction to game theory applications for students of engineering and computer science Materials presented sequentially and in an easy-to-understand fashionTopics explore zero-sum, non-zero-sum, and dynamics gamesMATLAB commands are included  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCooperative games (Mathematics)vTextbooks. 0aGame theoryvTextbooks. 0aNoncooperative games (Mathematics)vTextbooks. 7aMATHEMATICS / Game Theory.2bisacsh  aMATLAB.  aMinimax Theorem.  aN-player game.  aNash equilibrium.  aSeparating Hyperplane Theorem.  aSudoku puzzle.  aaction space.  aaction.  aadmissible Nash equilibrium.  aadvertising campaign.  aalternate play.  aaverage security level.  abattle of the sexes.  abehavioral policy.  abehavioral saddle-point equilibrium.  abest-response equivalent games.  abilateral symmetric game.  abimatrix game.  abimatrix potential.  achicken game.  acircuit design.  acompletely mixed Nash equilibrium.  acomputational complexity.  acomputer science.  acongestion game.  acontinuous time cost-to-go.  acontinuous time differential.  acontinuous time dynamic programming.  acontinuous time dynamic.  aconvex analysis.  aconvex hull.  adecoupled game.  adesign methodology.  adifferential gam